Story 11 – Emotion Log Editor

Goal

Implement the Emotion Log Editor (EmotionLogEditorView) to enable users to create and edit emotion logs. This story creates a dedicated editor view that allows users to select emotions (required), add an optional note, and tag people and context (optional). The editor follows the same patterns established in JournalEditorView (Story 7) for consistency, uses the EmotionSelector and TagInput components created in Stories 3 and 4, and integrates with useEmotionLogStore from Story 9. The editor supports both create mode (/emotions/edit) and edit mode (/emotions/:id/edit), with validation ensuring at least one emotion is always selected.

⸻

Scope

1.	EmotionLogEditorView Component Creation
	•	Create src/views/EmotionLogEditorView.vue:
		•	Follow the same structure and patterns as JournalEditorView.vue
		•	Use AppShell layout (already handles top app bar and bottom nav)
		•	Container with responsive padding (container mx-auto px-4 py-6)
		•	Flex column layout with min-h-full for proper spacing
	•	Component structure:
		•	Loading state (when loading log data in edit mode)
		•	Timestamp display (current date/time in create mode, log's createdAt in edit mode)
		•	Emotions section (required) with EmotionSelector component
		•	Note field (optional) with textarea
		•	People tags section (optional) with TagInput component
		•	Context tags section (optional) with TagInput component
		•	Action buttons (Save and Cancel) at the bottom
		•	AppSnackbar for error messages and validation feedback

2.	Route Configuration
	•	Update src/router/index.ts to add two new routes:
		•	Route: /emotions/edit
			•	Name: 'emotions-edit'
			•	Component: EmotionLogEditorView
			•	Create mode (no ID parameter)
		•	Route: /emotions/:id/edit
			•	Name: 'emotions-edit-id'
			•	Component: EmotionLogEditorView
			•	Edit mode (ID parameter from route)
	•	Import EmotionLogEditorView component
	•	Follow the same pattern as journal editor routes (/journal/edit and /journal/:id/edit)

3.	AppShell Back Button Configuration
	•	Update src/components/AppShell.vue:
		•	Extend showBackButton computed property to include emotion editor routes:
			•	Check if route.path === '/emotions/edit'
			•	Check if route.path matches /^\/emotions\/[^/]+\/edit$/
		•	Extend backRoute computed property to return '/emotions' when on emotion editor routes
		•	This ensures back button appears and navigates correctly when editing emotion logs
		•	Follow the same pattern as journal editor routes

4.	Store Integration & Data Loading
	•	Import and initialize stores in EmotionLogEditorView:
		•	useEmotionLogStore() – to create/update emotion logs
		•	useEmotionStore() – to load emotions for EmotionSelector
		•	useTagStore() – to load tags for TagInput components
	•	On component mount:
		•	If in create mode (/emotions/edit):
			•	Initialize local state with empty values:
				•	selectedEmotionIds: []
				•	note: ''
				•	selectedPeopleTagIds: []
				•	selectedContextTagIds: []
			•	Load emotions if not already loaded (check emotionStore.isLoaded)
			•	Load people tags if empty (check tagStore.peopleTags.length)
			•	Load context tags if empty (check tagStore.contextTags.length)
		•	If in edit mode (/emotions/:id/edit):
			•	Extract log ID from route.params.id
			•	Load the log data using emotionLogStore or repository
			•	Pre-populate all fields with log data:
				•	selectedEmotionIds: log.emotionIds
				•	note: log.note || ''
				•	selectedPeopleTagIds: log.peopleTagIds || []
				•	selectedContextTagIds: log.contextTagIds || []
			•	Load emotions, people tags, and context tags (same as create mode)
	•	Handle loading states:
		•	Show loading indicator while loading log data (edit mode only)
		•	Show loading indicators for emotion/tag sections while data loads
		•	Use same loading pattern as JournalEditorView
	•	Handle error states:
		•	If log not found (edit mode), show error and navigate back to /emotions
		•	If loading fails, show error via AppSnackbar
		•	Allow user to retry or navigate back

5.	Emotions Section (Required)
	•	Display EmotionSelector component:
		•	Use v-model binding: v-model="selectedEmotionIds"
		•	Show loading state if emotions are not loaded yet
		•	Section header: "Emotions" with description explaining emotions are required
		•	Visual indication that this section is required (e.g., asterisk or "Required" label)
	•	Validation:
		•	Before saving, validate that selectedEmotionIds.length > 0
		•	If validation fails, show error message via AppSnackbar: "Please select at least one emotion"
		•	Prevent save if validation fails
		•	Validation error should be clear and user-friendly
	•	Layout:
		•	Section with border-top separator (border-t border-outline/40 pt-6)
		•	Header with title and description
		•	Loading state or EmotionSelector component

6.	Note Field (Optional)
	•	Display textarea for note input:
		•	Label: "Note" (optional)
		•	Placeholder: "Add a brief note about this emotion log (optional)"
		•	v-model binding: v-model="note"
		•	Textarea styling: same as JournalEditorView body textarea
		•	Rows: 4-6 (shorter than journal body since notes are brief)
		•	Resizable: resize-y
		•	Optional field indicator (e.g., "(optional)" in label or placeholder)
	•	Layout:
		•	Section with border-top separator
		•	Label and textarea
		•	No validation required (optional field)

7.	People Tags Section (Optional)
	•	Display TagInput component for people tags:
		•	Use v-model binding: v-model="selectedPeopleTagIds"
		•	Set tag-type prop: tag-type="people"
		•	Show loading state if people tags are not loaded yet
		•	Section header: "People" with description explaining this is optional
	•	Layout:
		•	Section with border-top separator
		•	Header with title and description
		•	Loading state or TagInput component
		•	Same pattern as JournalEditorView

8.	Context Tags Section (Optional)
	•	Display TagInput component for context tags:
		•	Use v-model binding: v-model="selectedContextTagIds"
		•	Set tag-type prop: tag-type="context"
		•	Show loading state if context tags are not loaded yet
		•	Section header: "Context" with description explaining this is optional
	•	Layout:
		•	Section with border-top separator
		•	Header with title and description
		•	Loading state or TagInput component
		•	Same pattern as JournalEditorView

9.	Timestamp Display
	•	Display timestamp at the top of the editor:
		•	In create mode: Show current date/time
			•	Format: "Today, HH:MM" if today, otherwise full date/time
			•	Use same formatting logic as JournalEditorView
		•	In edit mode: Show log's createdAt timestamp
			•	Use formatEntryDate() utility function
			•	Display: "Created on [formatted date]"
		•	Styling: text-sm text-on-surface-variant (muted styling)
		•	Position: Below top app bar, above form fields

10.	Save Functionality
	•	Save button (primary filled button):
		•	Label: "Save" (or "Saving..." when saving)
		•	Disabled state: isSaving || !isValid
		•	isValid: computed property checking selectedEmotionIds.length > 0
		•	Click handler: handleSave()
	•	handleSave() function:
		•	Validate that selectedEmotionIds.length > 0
		•	If validation fails, show error via AppSnackbar and return early
		•	Set isSaving to true
		•	Prepare payload:
			•	emotionIds: selectedEmotionIds.value
			•	note: note.value.trim() || undefined (empty string becomes undefined)
			•	peopleTagIds: selectedPeopleTagIds.value.length > 0 ? selectedPeopleTagIds.value : undefined
			•	contextTagIds: selectedContextTagIds.value.length > 0 ? selectedContextTagIds.value : undefined
		•	If in create mode:
			•	Call emotionLogStore.createLog(payload)
			•	On success: Navigate to /emotions, show success message via AppSnackbar
			•	On error: Show error message via AppSnackbar, keep isSaving false
		•	If in edit mode:
			•	Create updated log object:
				•	id: currentLog.value.id
				•	createdAt: currentLog.value.createdAt (preserve original)
				•	updatedAt: (will be set by store)
				•	...payload
			•	Call emotionLogStore.updateLog(updatedLog)
			•	On success: Navigate to /emotions, show success message via AppSnackbar
			•	On error: Show error message via AppSnackbar, keep isSaving false
		•	Set isSaving to false in finally block
		•	Handle errors gracefully (catch and display via AppSnackbar)

11.	Cancel Functionality
	•	Cancel button (text variant):
		•	Label: "Cancel"
		•	Disabled state: isSaving (prevent cancellation during save)
		•	Click handler: handleCancel()
	•	handleCancel() function:
		•	Navigate back to /emotions using router.push('/emotions')
		•	No confirmation dialog needed (user can always come back)
		•	No data loss warning (emotion logs are quick to recreate)

12.	Mode Detection
	•	Detect create vs edit mode:
		•	Use computed property: isEditMode
		•	Check: !!route.params.id && typeof route.params.id === 'string'
		•	Same pattern as JournalEditorView
	•	Use isEditMode to:
		•	Determine title in top app bar (via AppShell, but can be customized)
		•	Determine timestamp display (current time vs log's createdAt)
		•	Determine save behavior (createLog vs updateLog)
		•	Determine initial data loading (empty vs load from store)

13.	Data Loading in Edit Mode
	•	loadLog() function:
		•	Extract ID from route.params.id
		•	Set isLoading to true
		•	Try to find log in emotionLogStore.logs first (faster, already loaded)
		•	If not found in store, load from repository (emotionLogDexieRepository.getById)
		•	If log not found, show error and navigate to /emotions
		•	If found, sync log data to form fields using syncLogToForm()
		•	Handle errors gracefully (show error, navigate back)
		•	Set isLoading to false in finally block
	•	syncLogToForm() function:
		•	Set currentLog ref to the loaded log
		•	Set selectedEmotionIds: [...log.emotionIds]
		•	Set note: log.note || ''
		•	Set selectedPeopleTagIds: [...(log.peopleTagIds || [])]
		•	Set selectedContextTagIds: [...(log.contextTagIds || [])]
		•	Create copies of arrays to avoid reference issues

14.	Loading State Management
	•	Separate loading states for different sections:
		•	isLoading: boolean – loading log data (edit mode only)
		•	isEmotionDataLoading: boolean – loading emotions
		•	arePeopleTagsLoading: boolean – loading people tags
		•	areContextTagsLoading: boolean – loading context tags
	•	Computed properties for section loading:
		•	isEmotionSectionLoading: computed(() => isEmotionDataLoading.value || !emotionStore.isLoaded)
		•	Similar for tag sections
	•	Loading UI:
		•	Show "Loading entry..." when isLoading is true (edit mode)
		•	Show "Loading emotions..." when isEmotionSectionLoading is true
		•	Show "Loading people tags..." when arePeopleTagsLoading is true
		•	Show "Loading context tags..." when areContextTagsLoading is true
		•	Use same loading UI pattern as JournalEditorView

15.	Error Handling & User Feedback
	•	Loading errors:
		•	If log not found (edit mode), show error via AppSnackbar and navigate to /emotions
		•	If emotions fail to load, show error via AppSnackbar (but allow user to continue)
		•	If tags fail to load, show error via AppSnackbar (but allow user to continue)
	•	Save errors:
		•	If validation fails (no emotions selected), show error: "Please select at least one emotion"
		•	If createLog() throws error, catch and show error via AppSnackbar
		•	If updateLog() throws error, catch and show error via AppSnackbar
		•	Error messages should be user-friendly and actionable
	•	Success feedback:
		•	After successful save, show success message: "Emotion log saved successfully"
		•	Navigate to /emotions after successful save
	•	Use AppSnackbar for all user feedback (errors and success)

16.	Responsive Design & Accessibility
	•	Layout:
		•	Use container with mx-auto and px-4 for responsive padding
		•	Use flex-col for vertical layout
		•	Form fields should be full-width on mobile
		•	Action buttons should stack vertically on mobile, horizontally on desktop
	•	Accessibility:
		•	All form fields have proper labels
		•	Required fields are clearly marked (emotions section)
		•	Error messages are announced (via AppSnackbar)
		•	Loading states are announced (via disabled attributes and text)
		•	Keyboard navigation works (form fields, buttons)
		•	Focus management (AppShell handles top app bar focus)
	•	Touch targets:
		•	Buttons should have adequate touch target size (min-w-[44px] min-h-[44px])
		•	Form fields should have adequate padding for touch

